			'There are over 34 million people engaged in Pastoralism in India. The pastoralist communities of India have bred and nurtured several breeds of domesticated animals, and these pastoral systems house precious genetic resource which needs to be conserved and registered.\nSahjeevan, an organization based in Gujarat, organized an exhibition on Pastoralism in 2016. This exhibition led to formation of Center For Pastoralism, New Delhi an organization with a mandate to work on pastoral issues across India.\nResearch during the exhibition pointed to a diminishing indigenous wool economy, and this was a major source of discontent for sheep herders. CFP commissioned a study in 2018 to explore and understand the dynamics of the local sheep wool economies in different parts of India.\nThe first phase of the study focused on sheep herding systems in Gujarat, Rajasthan, Telangana, and Uttrakhand.\nA second phase of the study is scheduled to be commissioned in May 2019. This report presents the findings of first phase of the study.',
