		abstractNote:
			'Herders in the Sahel in general have few legal means available to protect their grazing lands from the encroachment of agriculture. In the Barkédji/Velingara area of northern Senegal a group of herders has taken up the challenge by soliciting their own private leasehold titles to the rangelands. This, however, appears a short-sighted solution as it opposes one of the major pillars of the extensive Sahelian grazing systems, free and open access to rangelands. The articles analyses some of the shortcomings of the legal practices in the area which have led to the present conflicts and points to some of the problems likely to arise as a consequence of the current laissez-faire attitude of government officials.',
