		abstractNote:
			'The personal interest and munificence of His Highness Maharao Vijayarajji made possible the ornithological survey of Kutch State which the author carried out in 1943 and 1944, the results of which are recorded in this book. The unique ‘ billiard-table flat strip of salt, barren, sandy waste ’ known as the Rann of Kutch is not only the only known nesting-place of the flamingo in India, but also offers matchless opportunities for the observation of bird migration. Like Karachi, Kutch is a great aerial junction. It lies on the eastern fringe of a broad stream of migration which flows from Central and Northern Asia southwards and westwards to Arabia, Abyssinia and even as far as South Africa; it receives many migrants and winter visitors too from Northern and Eastern Europe, and from the countries of the Middle East. There is no well-marked between the resident bird-population of Kutch and that of the adjacent dry areas of Sind, Northern Gujarat, Western Rajputana or the northern portions of the Kathiawar Peninsula, but in general the Great Rann seems to function as an efficient barrier to local migration so that the species in Kutch approximate more closely to those found in Gujarat than to those found in Sind and Baluchistan. Nearly a hundred species are depicted in the coloured plates specially painted for this book by Mrs. D. V. Cowen.',
