		abstractNote:
			'This paper examines the contrast between the formulation of problems in development policy, and the perspectives of villagers whose views have been subjugated and everyday activities criminalised, within this formulation. We attempt to identify the conditions in which certain demonstrably false ideas about environmental change have come to acquire validity in policy circles, while others, more correct and espoused by inhabitants, have been excluded from consideration and investigation.\nSeveral authors have recently spotlighted the presence of particular off-the-shelf ‘narratives’ current in development institutions, which come to define development problems and justify interventions, particularly in conditions where data is poor, time is short, national agendas are overruled and local consultation impossible (Hoben 1993; Roe 1991, 1995). Narrative construction is the stuff of synthesis overview writing within development agencies and policy research institutes, and of inter-agency analytical alignment in development approaches. Narratives help decision makers to fill confidently the gap between ignorance and expediency.',
